I am here to edit this post almost a year later, changing my 5 stars to 1. This is going to be the meanest review I've ever left. Wish it could be zero stars. After my hard drive provided by PCTECH crashed less than 9 months after it was provided to me, I brought it into a more reputable shop that ran a diagnostic and showed that I was given a USED drive from 2017, and not a brand new one as I was told when it was sold to me. Makes sense, considering how old, dirty and musty PCTECH's shop is. Furthermore, after testing the original drive I brought in initially, it was never faulty. The only issue there was turned out to be one of the cooling fans that I bought and replaced myself. So, in essence, this shady shop misdiagnosed my issue, told me I needed a new HD, claimed they replaced it with a new one while actually providing an old, used and untrustworthy piece of hardware. Stay as far away from this place as you can.< /Review>

< text>
TL;DR: Amazing PC Repair shop, with an amazing PC Technician. Eman, repaired my laptop that wouldn't power on at budget prices. Thanks!

My Story:
Let me start by saying that I originally took my MSI GS63VR Stealth Pro to Geek Squad at Best Buy for an issue, but after wasting 100 bucks they made my Laptop worse, as it did not turn on anymore.

Found this amazing repair shop that helped me with repairing not only the power issue, but they also fixed the USB issue I was having with my device.

My Experience:
This shop is situated on Van Nuys Boulevard, and Kalifa on the corner. The entrance is on Van Nuys Boulevard, do not park in the rear, as that is private parking for the other businesses.

As soon as I walked in, the PC Technician at the front, Eman S, was already working with a client, but kindly greeted me as I walked in and that he would be with me shortly. As he finished with his first client, he asked me what my issue was, and after a short story, he had a clear idea of what the issue could be, and advised me that it sounds like it could be a hardware issue, which Geek Squad told me was a software issue was completely wrong. He told me the price for the diagnostic and if he could get it repaired what the estimated final cost could be, he also asked me how soon I needed it back, and I told him anytime withing 7 days was fine.

Eman called me two days later (great time-frame), to inform me that he successfully repaired my laptop and for me to come pick up my device. As I got there, he insisted that I test all the aspects of my laptop to make sure that the service was completed. To my surprise during the test, I saw that my USB ports were working again, as it did not work before.

Prices:
$35.00 - Diagnostics
$195.00 - Repair (If successfully completed he would deduct the diagnostic price)
-------------------------
$160.00 - Final Price for completely fixing my laptop

Lastly, thank you to Eman for completely fixing my laptop, I was worried that my $1400 device would have gone down the trash after just two short years, but now it works like new. Definitely will be coming back for any other Computer issues or repairs, and definitely recommend that you should take your device here for repairs, instead of big business repair shops that only take your money.< /text>

No one could help me with my computer. Four trips to the "Geek Squad" at Best Buy got zilch. "Can't be done," they said. Two other attempts with "experts" also produced negative results. I gave up.
Then I found Eman in Craigslist, gave him a call, and he said he could help. His plan and explanation made more sense than anything I had heard, so I made the journey to his place of business (long trip).
Eman was courteous, kind, very patient (he explained everything and gave me choices), and his effort was quick and solved the numerous problems I had. The man took the word "vice" out of service and put a big smile on my face.
The travel time was well worth it, and in the process of solving my problems I feel that I have made a friend.

Thank you, Eman
your new friend, Jimmy Herring<//review>

< user_id>
102852887600332252245<//user_id>
< user_name>
Jay Rue<//user_name>
<Time>1583131204020<//Time>< rate>
3</rate>
< text>
This is a Korean Sashimi restaurant also known as a  HwehtJip.  Main difference of a Korean Hweh is that it comes with multiple items that are part of it - sort of a course meal and a utilitarian version of a Japanese omakase.  I really love an authentic Korean Hwejip!

With a party of 3 adults and a small child, we ordered a large sashimi plate for $100.  It came with many items.  Most were pretty standard Korean hweh-jip food offerings, and seemed fillerfoodish.  Sashimi plate featured mostly snapper and other white, translucent fleshy fish.  There was few thinly sliced - I think 4 slices - faytty tuna and salmon.

Staff was friendly and attentive at this small restaurant.

2 whole sea urchin rice came with this hweh dinner plate and was very tasty.  I think this was the highlight of this dinner.  It was a Large size sea urchin in it's natural shell.  And to finish off, a spicy fish soup which was a bit bland - I was hoping for a steamy, spicy broth with some fish bones.  As a drinker, I really look forward to the rich fish soup at korean hwehjip restaurants - it's an indicator of the restaurant and its overall dedication to food.  Although I was impressed by the sheer volume of food, I was a bit disappointed by its overall generic-ness(if that's a word).  We did not finish the pot.

Overall, this restaurant is clean and staff is attentive.  However, food is mediocre.  I think they may have stopped being innovative at one point - owners got too comfortable with their offerings and becoming cookie-cutter.

Dont go to this restaurant expecting a Japanese style sushi bar experience, as it is a very traditional Korean hwehjip

Despite some of it's short coming, I would recommend it for novice Korean sashimi patrons as it is a different experience from a Japanese sashimi.

It was nice to visit after 30 years to see this restaurant still in business with same name.< /text>

< review>
LOVE MAN SUN'S! I was finally able to try their uni bowls and I really wanted to get the large ($15), but they ran out :[ However, they were going to let me have two small ones for the same price (originally $9 each), but I decided to just get a small one to try and leave room for all the other delicious fish on the menu.  I was a little confused at first because, of course, I yelped this place before coming here and there were certain rolls that I saw in their pictures that were either not offered or not made the same way.  It just depends on which sushi chef is working that day.  Also, another turn off was that they gave us a menu, but it didn't have ANY rolls on it until I had to ask our server and then he brought out another menu.  Last turn off was that when I asked our server what each sashimi platter came with and he told me it was just up to the chef that day.... mmmkay.   I ended up ordering a small uni bowl, lobster roll, salmon crunch roll, and a sashimi platter.  Thankfully, everything was great so I will forgive all the weird/mysterious ordering at the beginning of the dinner.

Side notes:
-Small parking. You can try to find parking on the street as well, but I just parked at the lot next to it and nothing happened to my car. Wooooo
-Uni bowl isn't on the menu so you'll just have to ask for it.
-This place is Korean owned so you also get ban chan (side dishes)! Best of both worlds :)< /review>

<time>1417572204766< /time>< review>
I can see the hype of this place. It's located in DB/Walnut. It serves live fish and urchin (which is REALLY sad cuz you see the food moving). It has fresh sashimi.

FOOD:
I ordered the Man Sun dinner.
1. The sashimi was great. It was fresh.
2. The roll was standard. They ran out of tuna rolls so I got the California roll.
3. They forgot my salad... and then it took awhile but the salad was average. It's just a salad.
4. The tempura was good.
5. Green tea ice cream is always good.
6. Albacore roll: Meh, this didn't seem so fresh compared to the other sashimi. I was slightly disappointed.
7. The Lobster roll was pretty good except they skim you on the lobster.

SERVICE:
SUPER SLOW.
Good luck getting water.
Sometimes we had to remind them we were waiting on food. The place does always seem busy.

AMBIANCE: Small hole in the wall

NOTE:
The urchin bowl - the urchin is still alive while you're eating it so you're basically killing it by eating it ALIVE. My husband said it was ok. I was so upset with him.
There is also a live sashini - where the lobster/crab is still alive while you're eating it. It's really sad.

PARKING:
Free Parking lot or street

OVERALL: Meh, pass.< /review>
<user>110538517243108003786<//user><user_name>Laura S<//user_name>< Resp>
None< /Resp>
</record>
</dataset><record>
<Rate>5< /Rate><review>I can definitely see why people are raving about this pretty new Japanese restaurant! My boyfriend came here with his friends and liked it so much, he decided to bring his family and me back again a few days later.

Ambience: The restaurant itself is quite small, so apparently there is usually a long wait in order to be seated. They also don't accept reservations after 7 PM or so either, which is quite fair. And this place is quite popular among the younger crowd who don't seem to mind the hour or so wait that might occur. There isn't a parking lot either - besides street parking - or in the lot next door (which technically is a part of the farmer's market). We were lucky and were able to be seated in a private room. The pictures on the wall and the furniture all were very nice, but the food is the focal point of this review!

Food: People mainly come here for the uni bowl, which I think is a part of their sashimi deals. We ordered two large sashimi platters. Because they are a Korean owned restaurant, they served a lot of unique small dishes that included snails, kimchi, seaweed, shrimp, pancake, etc. The sashimi platter was enormous and had so many slices of fresh fish on it - salmon, yellowtail, albacore, lobster tail ... I can't eat fish, but I did taste the salmon and lobster tail, and both were amazing. Salmon was soft, succulent and overall smooth.

But the best part of the meal was indeed the uni bowl. Each person had their own individual uni shell that had sticky rice, seaweed, uni, fish egg, and picked radish. The sticky rice had good flavor, so when mixed with everything else (along with the sesame and seaweed), had incredible flavor that made me want to keep eating even though I was already pretty full.

After the uni bowl, they take the lobster (which is placed in front of you on the platter while it is slowly dying ... poor guy) to make into a lobster soup. Definitely hit the spot after a pretty full meal. And on top of that - vanilla ice cream to be served at the end!

Service: was amazing. Everybody was courteous and really nice. They stopped by often to make sure we were okay, and I felt like they were constantly bringing us food. Even though I couldn't eat a lot of the food that was served, I felt pretty full by the end!

tl;dr - I would DEFINITELY recommend this restaurant, especially if you are a fan of sushi or uni. Fresh fish, great quality, large quantity at a pretty good price! Just try to go early .. or if you don't mind, come with people you can chat with while waiting for a table. Definitely will come back to try that uni bowl again!</review>< date>
1416470924743< /date>

4< /rate>
< Text>
My first time at ACCD was Grad night with my friend who was a alumni and he wanted to show me the school. I was in awe and amazed with the program that I can see myself going there as well. I was so excited that everything that was displayed from Product Design to Photography to Illustration Design to Environmental Design to Automobile Design to Advertising, the list goes on!

I've never been to a graduation where I was super excited about seeing students that graduated with their accomplishments with their family near by to take pictures with them.

I recently attended their open house to see what night classes I wanted to try since I want to explore my creative side and it was really interesting where all the students backgrounds were. I felt really motivated to try something different from my current career and realized I'm not a lone. There's a lot of other students trying out other career goals to see what other opportunities they have a passion for!

The staff and advisors there were really welcoming and helpful.  They were very clear and concise about the program and how it will change your life. Overall, a great school if you want to become a designer!< /Text>

(Translated by Google) I went to Los Angeles to meet my old friend and visited for a long time. Many of the famous car designers have graduated from this university, which is an art university that puts emphasis on car design to the point that "A.C.C.D is car design." The location is Pasadena, located on the mountain side of Los Angeles, and becomes a high-class residential area (feels like Seijo).
If you drive about 30 minutes from downtown and climb a green hill, you will see a school building like a monotone museum. Because the total number of students is small, the site and school building are not very large, but the level of enhancement of facilities is wonderful. It is possible to freely use machines and abundant tools that create original parts designed with various materials.
There are no restaurants in the surrounding area, so there are plenty of shops and cafeterias.
Some of the ACCD car design departments work for automakers, but there are people who retire or take leave for study, and the challenges are really difficult. I am full of students who are always at school this week, but I think this is normal because I go to school with a purpose.
If you want to be active as a car designer in the future, we recommend that you visit the school once. It will surely be a good stimulus!

This is an authentic Sichuan restaurant. Interior is done with lots of carved wood and tables, chairs and benches are of nice real wood. Dishes are spicy with ma-la flavors. <userid>102050855867682345400</userid><Name>Kendra Vander Vliet< /Name><Date>1489027089349<//Date><Rate>3<//Rate><review>The restaurant is very stylish. I'll give it that.

The food we ordered was alright for the most part. You pay extra for the stylish decor but the food we got was pretty mediocre.

Braised Pork Belly: It was good but the veggie on the bottom was terribly salty.

Duck: Very tender and juicy and came with spicy salt. Was suppose to be served cold but our was warm, which wasn't bad for me.

Fried shrimp with oyster mushroom: The shrimp was fine but the mushroom was beyond over MSG salted and was inedible.

Dan Dan Noodles: This was my favorite of the night because it's generally safe to order and tastes good. No surprises there.

Sliced Beef with Green Pepper: Just terrible, the meat was very chewy and tough. Some of the worst beef I've ordered in an asian restaurant in the past few years.

If I was invited here, I'd come again. But I wouldn't return on my own.<//review>< pics>

< text>
Where to begin. I was on a business trip in L.A. and took my trusty old 99 Toyota Tacoma hauling a heavy load and made it to my location without a hitch. On my way home was a different story.
As I proceeded to climb on the grapevine, I noticed that the temperature started to rise and was going into the red! I was able to pull over at a gas station thinking my fluids were possibly low. I waited for a bit and topped off the radiator and went on my way. I thought it did the trick until about 5 minutes later, the temperature started to climb north once again.
Miraculously, I was able to hobble stopping every so often until I got to Bakersfield. At this point, I started to call friends that are mechanics only to tell me that it sounds like a major problem and to stay the night and have it looked at in the morning.
The people at the hotel suggested Scotty's and I figured I'd give him a call. He didn't answer right away so I tried 2 other auto repair places and Scotty's in between each call. One was a diesel mechanic and the other said he was booked for at least 2 days. On my third try, he answered and asked me to meet him in 30 minutes.
Scotty looks it over and gave me some possibilities as well and actually dropped some of the other vehicles he was working to diagnose my vehicle.
He found the problem and actually saved the day for me! He could have easily made money from me by telling me that the work needed was the same as what my mechanic friends told me. He opted to be honest rather than trying to make some extra money on someone he will never see again. His rates were exceptional and his work is very good. I would definitely give him my business over and over again. Too bad he doesn't live closer to me.

Rob Barreras</text>

<Gmap_id>0x80ea4245ad572895:0xce48033391efd006<//Gmap_id><Rate>5<//Rate>< Text>
Short version: Scotty's Auto Repair is a inexpensive auto repair that's convenient, a good price, and best of all, run by someone who really knows what he's doing. Scotty is very responsive to calls and texts, and responded within a few minutes every time. The shop is in a good location with plenty of parking too, literally right off the main freeway. He even checked and topped off my tires to get me ready for the trip back to San Diego. This kind of mechanic is sadly, a dying breed. Long version: I was driving from San Diego to San Francisco, when my worst nightmare happened. My car broke down about 70mi from Bakersfield, in what was essentially the middle of nowhere. My oil pan had 1 inch hole, cut by a piece of debris in the road. After calling AAA roadside premier, which put me in a rental and asked me where to tow my car, I asked them to tow it into town, Bakersfield, while I drove off to San Fran. I called a couple places, and most were either closed on Saturday or didn't have the time, or were way too expensive. I called Scotty's auto repair on Friday afternoon, and he was very helpful. When I mentioned I broke down while traveling and got stranded, he said he was able to squeeze me in on Saturday morning. This may not be that fast for everyone, as they seem to have lots of regular/long term clients, looking at other reviews. We discussed price and parts, and that was that. The next morning, I arrived in Bakersfield at 4am, hung out in the rental until thing opened, grabbed the parts, and headed to the shop. He was able to do the repair for a great price, and he charged a great price for the parts he did provide (Sealent, oil, many other shops overcharge). Within 3 hours of dropping it off, it was done, ran, tested, checked, and ready to go! Will I ever go back? Well, I don't live in Bakersfield, so HOPEFULLY not haha, but let's just Say I was lucky I broke down close to here. Oh, and if you have a AAA card, it's AAA certified shop, so if you tell them on the phone, they will discount you a bit too.</Text>

<Rating>5<//Rating>< Text>
Amazing service and beautiful shop. My wife and I were having our 2 year anniversary and I wanted to surprise her with a bouquet of peonies (her favorite). I had called around every florist in the area trying to find them, as it turns out it was graduation season and everyone was clean out. I called Patty at her shop around 11:30 while at work (super friendly and VERY helpful) and I got lucky. She had only a few left, in pink, and she actually set them aside for me so I could pick them up after work. When I arrived she had just returned from hand delivering flowers to a customer (pretty awesome service of you ask me) and had them ready. They were BEAUTIFUL! The burlap wrapping was a very nice touch. We chatted for a bit and I was on my merry way. When my wife came home from work and saw the flowers, she immediately broke into tears (of joy lol). Best anniversary surprise ever. Thank you Patty! I will definitely be back.</Text>

<review>My wife and I always get the same thing at Phil's, so I can't speak for their burgers or other sandwiches.  However, they make one of the best pastrami sandwiches in Los Angeles.  My wife and I stood in line at Wexler's Deli in Grand Central Market for half an hour because reviewers said it was the best pastrami sandwich in town, but I found the meat to be of the same quality as Phil's, only there was less of it and they charged us nearly twice as much.  Don't go to Wexler's; go to Phil's for pastrami.

(That said, the absolute best pastrami in LA is at Langer's Deli catercorner to MacArthur Park--one of the three worst neighborhoods in all of LA--only the sandwiches are as thin and expensive as Wexler's... but that pastrami is out of this world.)< /review>< Pictures>

<date>1305925501099</date>< Review>
LAMEST SALAD EVER!!!  I'm stuck at the office so a very nice co-worker offered to pick something up for me while he was dining at Phil's Diner.  After reviewing the menu online I jumped on the Grilled Veggie Salad (though there was no description, that should have been my red flag).  I had visions of zucchini and yellow squash and peppers - or any of the other gorgeous spring and  summer vegetables that are in season - served atop a bed of lush mixed greens.  Far from it!  What I received is a bland mix of warm, but not grilled, celery (yep, CELERY), carrots and water chestnuts over green lettuce.  This is a pathetic excuse for a Grilled Veggie Salad and hardly worth the 9 bucks it came to including tax.  I was so looking forward to trying Phil's and now I'm fairly certain that I'll never venture down there for another try.  Two big thumbs down.< /Review>

< name>
Angler For Life< /name>

[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMbsnFL3_s4cF-zNJFtbjT9ncRLz5hP60bt4HpH=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOx2Y4aYghIEAh1Aa9f6GLlF2kocYCK6GSFLydC=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPhcTQOeIoRfQKBZCM8lKju-8YFxzWa-Qelz6Z3=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN-vjMPaZy6N6NRcude1QJehcVwbzxdDwD75zms=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMouShldb_jUDEOHLrfNAf4N3RnzvskHtVJdYxa=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPbXUzHbBg-54qLw20mYatRNdQyjbJzdSlhHfwD=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOiEP06ViXD06gWqUx--pUXEmmXWjgNpCQw_jIy=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pictures>
< Review>
The wonderful aromas from the wood fired meats is the first thing that you'll agree with, the second is the unpretentious manner of the restaurant.  I recommend entering through the back door (on the north side of the building) and slowly walking through the restaurant as to see first hand what the other diners are having, while on your way to the hostess stand.  We arrived at 11:45 on a Thursday and were seated within 5 minutes, those that arrived at 12:15 had a 30 minute wait, so plan ahead.
The smoked salmon appetizer is worth a two hour drive by itself and its smart to order two (take one home for later that night) the French dip sandwich is the best you'll ever have and is big enough for two, as is the ceasar salad with rock shrimp.
This was a 5 star visit only because 7 stars isn't an option.< /Review>

< Name>
Jeffrey Shaikh<//Name>
< Text>
I've been dining at Rutherford Grill for years. I love this place. The service is awesome and the staff is so friendly. It's upscale casual and very comfortable. The first time I sat at the bar and had a martini, they do make an excellent martini. The bartender actually refreshed my martini for me with an ice-cold glass... excellent. Very attentive staff. I usually get the salmon, it's excellent. They do change the menu slightly, based on season and availability, but it's always good. Last weekend the salmon came with coconut rice. Wow, it was delicious and the salmon was perfectly cooked. It is sometimes a wait to get in, as they are always busy on the weekend, but grab a cocktail and sit out on the patio. The wait is worth it.</Text>

<text>Update: Third time here and it was wonderful once again!!! I‚Äôm adding new pics be prepared for mouthwatering experience!!!

This is only my second time here. And both time we had to a wait time of at least one hour. If you‚Äôre out at the wineries and decide you want to eat here make sure to make reservations. So we decided to sit at the bar and indulge in their appetizers and drinks instead. The appetizers were amazing and desserts were a delight!

We ordered jalape√±o corn bread, spinach and artichoke dip with chips,  home smoked Salmon and deviled eggs. The jalape√±o corn bread was serve on a circular pan that had crunchiness around it but moist inside. The jalape√±o was not over power which made the bread unique, not to mention it was made from scratch....The smoked salmon was a delight, it came with this dill sauce instead of tartar sauce of some kind. That sauce actually compliments the salmon very well.

For desserts we went with apple walnut cobbler with vanilla ice cream, which came in warm and toasty and a spoonful of ice cream to the bite was so delightful! The open faced Oreo ice cream was served as an ice cream sandwich in a bed of warm chocolate sauce, the servings were big enough to share unless you just love dessert then get your own :D.

Last but not least they had an amazing list of wine. If you like red blends, I recommend the scouts honor red blends. It has a mixed of Zinfandel, Charbono, petite Sirah, and Syrah!!! At first sip you will find it amazing on the palate throughout with a smooth finish!<//text><gmapID>0x80845698b7c6cf11:0x745f1bcf2fee460d<//gmapID><Rating>4</Rating><date>1569974629656< /date></record>

<text>Unless I want seafood, this restaurant is my favorite. PERIOD. I drove over an hour to get here with friends for lunch. That much favorite! The corned bread is so famous, when you Google "Rutherford Grill", the corned bread is the second thing to come up. That's how much people love it and it's not even on the menu! I used to order all different items off their menus but now I only get the pork ribs. You don't even need a knife. The meat just falls off the bone. And the bbq sauce is not overwhelming - it's just right. Service is always perfect too. If I had to think hard about something negative, it could be certain sitting areas are louder than others, but all acceptable. Wish they used Open Table for reservations too.  Happy eating!< /text>< Pics>

Rutherford Grill is always my top recommendation for anyone traveling through the area. The artichokes. The prime rib sandwich.  And most extraordinary of all... the prime rib! < username>
Naomi Steenson</username>
<Date>1559080852656<//Date><rate>5< /rate>< text>
This place never disappoints! Although it is generally packed, the host staff make every effort to expedite seating. Had the Ahi Tuna and Mango salad and it was off the charts, the ahi superbly prepared (seared rare) and salad items all fresh and in optimal consistency. Dressing and accompaniments (wasabi, & ginger) made the salad perfect. Split the cornbread baked in a skillet with my companion and that was unbelievably awesome in flavor, texture and so rich, no butter was needed. Even though you're in wine country, the cocktails are as good as any celebrated bay area cocktail bar. You can't go wrong here.<//text>

<review>Nice place, albeit a bit pricy. (It is Napa Valley, after all). Beware if you're coming without a reservation - it took nearly two hours to be seated without one. The outside waiting area is very nice and there is an outdoor bar that operates during the summer. Service is very good, wonderful staff both at the bar and tableside. Ambiance inside can be a bit dark and noisy - you may have to raise your voice to be heard amongst your party.

Pro Tip: There's no corkage fee here so you can bring your own wine (maybe that you've purchased from one of your winery visits!) and they'll open it for you.< /review>< Name>
Kai Groves< /Name>

The Rutherford Grill was everything it's cracked up to be. I had a combination plate with perfectly cooked tri-tip and a very inventive squash enchilada with an excellent cumin infused red chili sauce. Wife had a bbq combo with tender smoky ribs and a plump chicken quarter, and the sides were as good as the main dishes. All the servers were in black slacks and crisp white shirts and blouses and the service was excellent. Cool jazz played in the background. A little pricey (but not for Napa), and a thoroughly delightful experience.< /Review>

<review>Don't go there if you have you have a disability, especially if you have a service dog.  They may be friendly to other dogs, but not to service dogs.  I waited 20 minutes with my large service dog while 2 dozen other people were seated with parties anywhere from 2 to 8 people.  When I questioned this practice the answer was that they could not seat me in a large booth meant for up to 8 people but they could seat a party of 4 there.  I was offered a table outside but in the sun only.  Pet dogs and their owners were offered shaded tables.  When I finally was seated, by the kitchen, I ordered the rotisserie chicken with french fries.  The waitress that tossed it at me (not my assigned server) could not look at me, maybe because the chicken was lukewarm or because she brought mashed potatoes instead of the french fries I had ordered.  No repeat visits from me and my service dog .< /review>< pics>

<Review>Don't go there if you have you have a disability, especially if you have a service dog.  They may be friendly to other dogs, but not to service dogs.  I waited 20 minutes with my large service dog while 2 dozen other people were seated with parties anywhere from 2 to 8 people.  When I questioned this practice the answer was that they could not seat me in a large booth meant for up to 8 people but they could seat a party of 4 there.  I was offered a table outside but in the sun only.  Pet dogs and their owners were offered shaded tables.  When I finally was seated, by the kitchen, I ordered the rotisserie chicken with french fries.  The waitress that tossed it at me (not my assigned server) could not look at me, maybe because the chicken was lukewarm or because she brought mashed potatoes instead of the french fries I had ordered.  No repeat visits from me and my service dog .</Review>< pics>

<Pics>None</Pics><Gmap_id>0x80845698b7c6cf11:0x745f1bcf2fee460d< /Gmap_id>< review>
Very consistent Food, service and atmosphere.  I get the French dip and Cole slaw. My wife gets the fish sandwich and salad.  The ribs are the best in the Napa Valley as well.

Right on the highway and easy to find.  The outside
Area of s really nice for a drink.

<Text>We had such a lovely experience here. We were at the Beaulieu tasting room, which happened to be next door, when we discovered this lovely restaurant. We walked over, and put our name on the list - about a 75 minute wait. Since they have FREE bottle service, we had brought a bottle with us from Beaulieu and in total spent about 2 hours sitting at the bar with our wine. To be honest, I think they forgot us, but when we finally went up to ask, they had us seated at a table within 5 minutes.
The food was quite enjoyable. We had the ribs and the enchilada/tri-tip plate. We shared the oreo ice cream sandwich for dessert, and that was really good too. We'll be coming back here for sure - although hopefully next time we won't be waiting for 2 hours!< /Text><Time>1488672642773<//Time><Rate>5< /Rate></record></dataset><record>

< Review>
It was a pleasant experience as usual...we always look forward to the best margartitas, vegi burgers and prime rib french dip - our fave stop in Napa. Tonight was busy - 2 hr wait for a table so we ordered our food to-go. Ordered our drinks at the bar...then a table on the patio opened up so we sat and enjoyed our $30 drinks...we ordered a few apps then our dinner (take out) was ready and we ate it at out table. No big deal...$30 for 2 drinks, $20 in apps, and $36 (not including tip) and guess what we were told that we had to leave by the manager. What a joke! Did I mention that they were no longer serving dinner on the patio! Long story short - we ordered drinks at the bar, ordered apps at the table and food to-go and we were told to leave because we were eating our dinner out of take out containers. Rutherford Grill - you truly have the WORST MANAGEMENT SKILLS EVER. Your staff is amazing however your management made us feel terrible for dining at your establishment. Sad that we spend a pretty penny to feel like 3rd class citizens - we will never recommend your establishment or be back...saddest thing is that it was the management not the staff... in my experience it's the management cleaning up the staffs mess; not in this case. Shame on you MANAGER!.<//Review>
